"Skip to content\nChat history\nNew chat\nSearch chats\nImages\nApps\nDeep research\nSee plans and pricing\nSettings\nHelp\n\nGet responses tailored to you\n\nLog in to get answers based on saved chats, plus create images and upload files.\n\nLog in\nChatGPT\nLog in\nSign up for free\n\nThis is a copy of a shared ChatGPT conversation\n\nReport conversation\n\nI’ll verify Meta’s current DINOv3 licensing from primary sources, then compare it with Apache 2.0 and distinguish code/library terms from model-weight terms where relevant.\n\nI found DINOv3 uses Meta’s custom license, not Apache 2.0, with restrictions applying to both code and model weights. I’m also checking two Meta-hosted license versions and will flag the discrepancy.\n\nThought for 4m 42s\n\nI’m assuming “standard Apache license” means Apache License 2.0. This is not legal advice, but it should give you the practical picture.\n\nBottom line\n\nDINOv3 is not under Apache 2.0. Meta’s DINOv3 repository says the code and model weights are released under a custom DINOv3 License. That license covers not just source code, but also documentation, model code, trained weights, inference code, training code, fine-tuning code, and related materials. \nGitHub\n+1\n\nIn plain English: you can use DINOv3 commercially in many ordinary projects, but it is not a normal permissive open-source license like Apache 2.0. It has extra restrictions, including prohibited uses, trade-control restrictions, a reverse-engineering restriction, redistribution rules for DINO materials and derivatives, an indemnity obligation, and a clause letting Meta modify the agreement over time. \nAI Meta\n+1\n\nWhat the DINOv3 license allows\n\nThe license gives you a worldwide, royalty-free, non-exclusive, non-transferable, limited license to use, copy, reproduce, distribute, modify, and create derivative works of the DINO materials. \nGitHub\n\nThat means you can generally:\n\nrun DINOv3 in your own project;\n\nuse it as a feature extractor or vision backbone;\n\nmodify the code;\n\nfine-tune or adapt model-related components;\n\ncreate derivative works;\n\nuse it in commercial software, subject to the license restrictions.\n\nMeta’s own blog describes the release as being under a commercial license, and the GitHub license grant does not limit use to research or non-commercial purposes. \nAI Meta\n+1\n\nThe main differences from Apache 2.0\nTopic\tApache 2.0\tDINOv3 License\tPractical meaning\nLicense type\tStandard, OSI-approved permissive open-source license. Apache 2.0 appears on OSI’s approved license list. \nOpen Source Initiative\n\tCustom Meta license. Not the same as Apache/MIT/BSD.\tCompanies often need a separate legal review before approving it.\nCommercial use\tAllowed for any field of use.\tCommercial use appears allowed, but with use restrictions. \nAI Meta\n+1\n\tYou can likely use it in a product, but not in every kind of product.\nField-of-use restrictions\tApache does not ban particular industries or use cases. OSI’s definition says open-source licenses must not restrict fields of endeavor. \nOpen Source Initiative\n\tDINOv3 bans or restricts uses involving ITAR, military/warfare purposes, nuclear industries/applications, espionage, guns, illegal weapons, sanctions, and trade controls. \nGitHub\n\tThis is the biggest difference. DINOv3 is “commercially usable,” but not “use for anything.”\nRedistribution\tYou can redistribute source or object code, modified or unmodified, if you include the license, mark changed files, preserve notices, and handle NOTICE files. \nApache Software Foundation\n\tIf you distribute DINO materials or derivative works, you must do so under the DINOv3 License and provide a copy of that agreement. \nGitHub\n\tDo not relicense DINOv3 code/weights/fine-tuned derivatives as Apache-only, MIT-only, or proprietary-only.\nYour own code\tYour own additions can usually be under your own license, including proprietary terms, as long as Apache conditions are met. \nApache Software Foundation\n\tYour own project can still have its own license, but DINO materials and derivatives must remain under DINOv3 terms when distributed.\tKeep DINOv3 as a separately tracked third-party component.\nPatent license\tApache 2.0 has an explicit patent grant from contributors. \nApache Software Foundation\n\tDINOv3 has a broad IP-use grant, but not the same explicit Apache-style contributor patent license. \nGitHub\n\tHigher legal uncertainty than Apache, especially for patent-sensitive companies.\nReverse engineering\tApache 2.0 does not generally prohibit reverse engineering.\tDINOv3 says your use must not involve or encourage reverse engineering, decompiling, or discovering underlying components. \nGitHub\n\tThis is unusual compared with normal open-source licenses.\nResearch publication\tApache 2.0 has no special publication-acknowledgment rule.\tIf you publish research results using DINO materials, you must acknowledge DINO materials. \nGitHub\n\tAcademic or benchmark papers need explicit acknowledgment.\nIndemnity\tApache 2.0 has limited indemnity only if you choose to offer warranties/support/liability while redistributing. \nApache Software Foundation\n\tDINOv3 requires you to indemnify Meta for third-party claims arising from your use or distribution. \nGitHub\n\tMore risk is shifted to you than under Apache.\nLicense stability\tApache 2.0 is a fixed standard license.\tMeta may modify the agreement, and continued use after modification means agreement to the modification. \nGitHub\n\tYou should monitor license changes, especially in production/commercial settings.\nAccess to model weights\tApache-licensed code is typically downloadable without approval.\tDINOv3 model access requires accepting license agreements; Hugging Face notes an information-review process and excludes comprehensively sanctioned jurisdictions. \nHugging Face\n\tOperationally, this is more gated than a normal Apache project.\nHow you can use DINOv3 in a project\n\nFor a private/internal project, you can generally download/use the materials after accepting the license, run inference, test it, build prototypes, train adapters, or evaluate it—provided your use does not fall into the prohibited categories and you comply with privacy, data-protection, sanctions, and trade-control laws. \nGitHub\n\nFor a commercial SaaS product, you can likely use DINOv3 as a backend model or feature extractor, but your customer-facing terms should prevent users from using the DINOv3-powered functionality for prohibited purposes such as military/warfare, nuclear applications, espionage, guns, illegal weapons, or export-controlled uses. The license says you may not use or permit others to use the materials for those prohibited end uses. \nGitHub\n\nFor a distributed application where you ship DINOv3 code, weights, modified weights, or derivative works to customers, you need to include the DINOv3 License and make sure those DINO-related components are distributed under DINOv3 terms. Your own surrounding application can still be proprietary or Apache-licensed, but the DINOv3 pieces should not be presented as Apache-licensed. \nGitHub\n\nFor an open-source project, you should not simply list the whole repository as Apache 2.0 if it includes DINOv3 materials. A cleaner approach is to keep your own code under Apache 2.0 if you want, but put DINOv3 in a separate dependency/model section with its own license notice and usage restrictions.\n\nFor fine-tuning or adapters, the license says that, as between you and Meta, you own derivative works and modifications you make, but distribution of DINO materials and derivative works is still subject to the DINOv3 License. \nGitHub\n So a safe approach is: do not distribute fine-tuned DINOv3 weights or DINO-derived components under Apache-only or proprietary-only terms without legal review.\n\nImportant discrepancy I found\n\nThere are two official-looking Meta license texts online. The GitHub/Hugging Face version is dated August 19, 2025 and says redistribution requires providing the DINOv3 License. \nGitHub\n+1\n An older Meta license page dated August 14, 2025 additionally says redistributors must prominently display “Built with DINOv3” on a related website, UI, blog post, about page, or product documentation. \nAI Meta\n\nBecause the repository and Hugging Face models point to the later August 19 text, that appears to be the current operative version for those artifacts. For a commercial product, I would still flag this discrepancy for legal review before distribution.\n\nPractical compliance checklist\n\nUse this approach for a project:\n\nTreat DINOv3 as a separate third-party component, not as Apache-licensed code.\n\nKeep a copy of the exact DINOv3 License version you accepted.\n\nRecord who accepted the license and for which entity, since the license is non-transferable.\n\nDo not use it in banned areas: military/warfare, ITAR-controlled uses, nuclear, espionage, guns, illegal weapons, sanctioned jurisdictions, or trade-controlled uses.\n\nIf distributing DINOv3 materials or derivatives, include the DINOv3 License and do not relicense those parts as Apache/MIT/proprietary-only.\n\nIf using it in SaaS, add customer-use restrictions that mirror the DINOv3 prohibited-use terms.\n\nIf publishing research, acknowledge DINOv3.\n\nMonitor the license page/repository for changes because the license allows Meta to modify the agreement.\n\nIn one sentence: DINOv3 can be usable in commercial projects, but it is a custom, restricted Meta license—not a normal Apache-style permissive open-source license.\n\nSources\nCan I run dinov3 on my Mac book pro m1?\n\nI’ll verify the current DINOv3 docs and Apple Silicon/PyTorch support, then translate that into what an M1 MacBook Pro can realistically run.\n\nThought for 3m 12s\n\nYes. You can run DINOv3 on a MacBook Pro M1 for inference / feature extraction, especially with the smaller models. You should not expect to train DINOv3 from scratch on an M1, and the largest 7B model is generally unrealistic on normal M1 MacBook Pro memory.\n\nThe practical answer is:\n\nMacBook Pro M1 memory\tRecommended DINOv3 model\n8 GB RAM\tfacebook/dinov3-vits16-pretrain-lvd1689m or dinov3-convnext-tiny\n16 GB RAM\tViT-S, ViT-S+, ViT-B, ConvNeXt Tiny/Small/Base\n32 GB+ RAM\tViT-L may be usable for inference; ViT-H+ may be possible but heavy\n64 GB+ RAM\tYou can experiment with bigger models, but ViT-7B is still inconvenient on Mac\n\nDINOv3 includes models from 21M parameters up to 6.7B parameters, including ViT-S, ViT-B, ViT-L, ViT-H+, ConvNeXt variants, and ViT-7B. Meta’s repo lists ViT-S at 21M, ViT-B at 86M, ViT-L at 300M, ViT-H+ at 840M, and ViT-7B at 6,716M parameters. \nGitHub\n Hugging Face also lists DINOv3 checkpoints and supports them through Transformers; the model pages say you need to accept/share contact information before accessing the weights. \nHugging Face\n\nUse MPS, not CUDA\n\nYour M1 does not use NVIDIA CUDA. It uses Apple’s Metal Performance Shaders, exposed in PyTorch as the mps device. Apple says PyTorch uses the MPS backend for GPU acceleration on Apple silicon Macs. \nApple Developer\n\nOne important limitation: Hugging Face notes that on Apple Silicon, the entire model must fit in unified memory; unlike CUDA setups, device_map=\"auto\" cannot split/offload layers to CPU in the same way. \nHugging Face\n So model size matters a lot.\n\nRecommended setup\n\nUse the Hugging Face Transformers path rather than trying to run the full Meta training repo locally.\n\nBash\npython3 -m venv .venv\nsource .venv/bin/activate\n\npip install -U torch torchvision transformers pillow huggingface_hub\nhuggingface-cli login\n\nThen accept access to the DINOv3 model on Hugging Face before running it.\n\nMinimal M1 inference script\n\nStart with the small ViT-S model:\n\nPython\nimport torch\nfrom PIL import Image\nfrom transformers import AutoImageProcessor, AutoModel\n\nmodel_name = \"facebook/dinov3-vits16-pretrain-lvd1689m\"\n\ndevice = \"mps\" if torch.backends.mps.is_available() else \"cpu\"\nprint(\"Using device:\", device)\n\nprocessor = AutoImageProcessor.from_pretrained(model_name)\nmodel = AutoModel.from_pretrained(model_name).to(device)\nmodel.eval()\n\nimage = Image.open(\"your_image.jpg\").convert(\"RGB\")\ninputs = processor(images=image, return_tensors=\"pt\").to(device)\n\nwith torch.inference_mode():\n    outputs = model(**inputs)\n\n# Global image embedding\nembedding = outputs.pooler_output\nprint(embedding.shape)\n\nIf you hit an unsupported MPS operation, try:\n\nBash\nexport PYTORCH_ENABLE_MPS_FALLBACK=1\n\nHugging Face specifically recommends this fallback variable for unsupported MPS operations. \nHugging Face\n\nWhich model should you try first?\n\nUse this first:\n\nfacebook/dinov3-vits16-pretrain-lvd1689m\n\nIt is the safest starting point on an M1. Hugging Face lists that model as 21.6M parameters, with usage through AutoImageProcessor and AutoModel. \nHugging Face\n\nThen, if your Mac has enough memory, try:\n\nfacebook/dinov3-vitb16-pretrain-lvd1689m\n\nI would avoid starting with:\n\nfacebook/dinov3-vit7b16-pretrain-lvd1689m\n\nThe 7B model is much too large for casual local use on most MacBook Pro M1 configurations. In raw FP32 terms, 6.7B parameters alone implies roughly 26–27 GB just for weights, before runtime overhead and activations.\n\nWhat you can realistically do on M1\n\nYou can use DINOv3 locally for:\n\nimage embeddings;\n\nimage similarity search;\n\nvisual feature extraction;\n\nk-NN or linear classification using frozen features;\n\nprototypes for retrieval, clustering, anomaly detection, or small downstream tasks.\n\nThat matches the intended “vision backbone” usage described in the DINOv3 model card: image classification with simple classifiers, image retrieval, depth/segmentation with lightweight heads, object discovery, tracking, and similar downstream tasks. \nHugging Face\n\nYou should not expect to do serious DINOv3 pretraining on a MacBook Pro M1. Meta’s own training example for ViT-L uses 4 H100-80GB nodes / 32 GPUs, and the exact ViT-7B setup uses 32 nodes / 256 GPUs. \nGitHub\n\nPlain-English answer\n\nYes, run DINOv3 on your MacBook Pro M1, but use it as a frozen feature extractor and start with ViT-S or ConvNeXt Tiny. Use PyTorch + Hugging Face Transformers + the mps device. Avoid the 7B model unless you have a very high-memory Apple Silicon machine and are prepared for slow, experimental local inference.\n\nSources\n\nI’ll make this paste-ready for Codex, assuming you are inside a new project folder and want a local .venv with no Conda.\n\nThought for 2m 58s\n\nUse this revised version. It assumes Codex is already running inside the project folder.\n\nSet up this current folder as a local Python project for a fast DINOv3 + UMAP + FiftyOne prototype.\n\nImportant:\n- I am already inside the project root.\n- Do not create a nested dinov3-map/ folder.\n- Use the current working directory as the project root.\n- First run pwd and confirm the project path.\n- Do not use Conda, Miniconda, Mambaforge, or CUDA.\n- Create the virtual environment inside this project at:\n  .venv\n- Use Python 3.11 if available.\n- This is for a MacBook M1 Pro.\n- Use PyTorch MPS when available.\n- Keep DINOv3 frozen.\n- No classifier.\n- No fine-tuning.\n- Goal: images → DINOv3 embeddings → UMAP 2D map → FiftyOne visualization.\n\nCreate this structure in the current folder:\n\nAGENTS.md\nREADME.md\nrequirements.txt\nimages/\noutputs/\nscripts/\n  check_env.py\n  extract_embeddings.py\n  make_umap.py\n  view_fiftyone.py\n\nSet up the virtual environment:\n\npython3.11 -m venv .venv\nsource .venv/bin/activate\npython -m pip install --upgrade pip setuptools wheel\n\nInstall these packages:\n\ntorch\ntorchvision\ntransformers\nhuggingface_hub\npillow\nnumpy\npandas\ntqdm\numap-learn\nscikit-learn\nfiftyone\n\nWrite requirements.txt with those dependencies.\n\nCreate scripts/check_env.py that:\n- prints Python version\n- prints torch version\n- prints whether torch.backends.mps.is_available()\n- prints FiftyOne version\n- exits cleanly\n\nCreate scripts/extract_embeddings.py that:\n- recursively scans images/ for jpg, jpeg, png, webp\n- uses facebook/dinov3-vits16-pretrain-lvd1689m\n- uses Hugging Face Transformers AutoImageProcessor and AutoModel\n- uses device = \"mps\" if available, otherwise \"cpu\"\n- uses outputs.pooler_output as the global image embedding\n- L2-normalizes embeddings\n- skips broken images gracefully\n- saves outputs/embeddings.npy as float32\n- saves outputs/manifest.csv with columns:\n  index,path,filename,width,height\n- has CLI flags:\n  --image-dir images\n  --out-dir outputs\n  --batch-size 8\n\nCreate scripts/make_umap.py that:\n- loads outputs/embeddings.npy and outputs/manifest.csv\n- runs UMAP with cosine metric\n- default parameters:\n  n_neighbors=40\n  min_dist=0.05\n  n_components=2\n  random_state=42\n- saves outputs/map.csv with:\n  index,path,filename,x,y\n- has CLI flags:\n  --embeddings outputs/embeddings.npy\n  --manifest outputs/manifest.csv\n  --out outputs/map.csv\n  --n-neighbors 40\n  --min-dist 0.05\n\nCreate scripts/view_fiftyone.py that:\n- loads outputs/map.csv\n- creates or reloads a FiftyOne dataset named dinov3_map\n- adds each image as a FiftyOne sample\n- stores x and y coordinates as sample fields\n- launches the FiftyOne app\n- if direct scatterplot visualization is possible, use the UMAP coordinates\n- otherwise launch the dataset browser and document the limitation clearly\n- has CLI flag:\n  --map outputs/map.csv\n\nCreate README.md with exact commands:\n\nsource .venv/bin/activate\n\npython scripts/check_env.py\n\nhuggingface-cli login\n\npython scripts/extract_embeddings.py \\\n  --image-dir images \\\n  --out-dir outputs \\\n  --batch-size 8\n\npython scripts/make_umap.py \\\n  --embeddings outputs/embeddings.npy \\\n  --manifest outputs/manifest.csv \\\n  --out outputs/map.csv \\\n  --n-neighbors 40 \\\n  --min-dist 0.05\n\npython scripts/view_fiftyone.py \\\n  --map outputs/map.csv\n\nAlso include troubleshooting notes:\n- If MPS is not available, fall back to CPU.\n- If Hugging Face model download fails, remind me to accept the DINOv3 model license on Hugging Face and run huggingface-cli login.\n- If FiftyOne fails to launch, print the local app URL and explain how to retry.\n- If Python 3.11 is unavailable, stop and tell me which Python versions were found.\n\nCreate AGENTS.md with:\n- No Conda.\n- No CUDA.\n- No classifier.\n- No fine-tuning.\n- Keep scripts simple.\n- Cache all outputs under outputs/.\n- Optimize for a fast prototype on about 2,000 images.\n- Use global DINOv3 embeddings first; patch features are a later experiment.\n\nAfter creating the files, run:\n\nsource .venv/bin/activate\npython scripts/check_env.py\n\nThen summarize:\n- current project path\n- where the virtual environment was created\n- which packages were installed\n- whether MPS is available\n- the exact next command I should run\n\nKey change from the previous version: Codex should not create ~/Projects/dinov3-map anymore. It should treat the folder you are already in as the project root and create only ./.venv, ./scripts, ./images, and ./outputs.\n\nI would like dino and all the other frameworks/libraries to sit in a specific subfolder, not in the project root. \nI also want to install https://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/en/model_doc/siglip2\nI have created a hugginface account, shall I generate access tokens?\n\n\nI’ll revise the Codex handover so the environment, model cache, downloaded weights, and outputs live under a dedicated subfolder, then address Hugging Face tokens separately.\n\nThought for 5m 16s\n\nYes: generate a Hugging Face access token.\n\nUse a read-only or fine-grained read token, not a write token. DINOv3 access is gated, so your machine needs authentication after you accept the model terms. Hugging Face recommends user access tokens for apps/notebooks, and read tokens are enough for downloading models; fine-grained tokens are better if you want to limit access to specific models. \nHugging Face\n\nSigLIP2 itself is public, but it also loads through Hugging Face Transformers, so using the same login/token is fine. SigLIP2 is a multilingual vision-language encoder family; for your prototype, use it as the “semantic / text-aligned” comparison model next to DINOv3. \nHugging Face\n+1\n\nBetter folder strategy\n\nUse this:\n\nproject-root/\n  _runtime/\n    venv/\n    hf/\n    fiftyone/\n      mongo/\n      datasets/\n      zoo/\n  images/\n  outputs/\n  scripts/\n  requirements.txt\n  AGENTS.md\n  README.md\n  .gitignore\n\nMeaning:\n\n_runtime/venv     = installed Python libraries\n_runtime/hf       = downloaded Hugging Face models: DINOv3, SigLIP2, etc.\n_runtime/fiftyone = FiftyOne local database/cache\n\nThis keeps the project root clean.\n\nImportant distinction:\n\nDINOv3 and SigLIP2 are not “installed libraries.”\nThey are model weights downloaded by transformers into the Hugging Face cache.\n\nThe actual Python libraries are:\n\ntorch\ntransformers\nhuggingface_hub\nfiftyone\numap-learn\nscikit-learn\n\nThose will live inside:\n\n_runtime/venv/\n\nHugging Face supports moving its local cache via HF_HOME and HF_HUB_CACHE. By default it uses ~/.cache/huggingface, but we will override that to keep models inside your project. \nHugging Face\n\nFiftyOne also supports local config/env variables such as FIFTYONE_DATABASE_DIR, FIFTYONE_DEFAULT_DATASET_DIR, and FIFTYONE_DATASET_ZOO_DIR, so we can keep its database and dataset files under _runtime/fiftyone/. \nFiftyOne\n+1\n\nAccess token recommendation\n\nCreate:\n\nToken name: dinov3-map-local\nRole: read\n\nor, better:\n\nRole: fine-grained\nAccess: read access to the DINOv3 model repos you need\n\nDo not paste the token into code. Use:\n\nBash\nhuggingface-cli login\n\nor:\n\nBash\nhf auth login\n\nThe token will be stored locally. Since we will set HF_HOME=./_runtime/hf, the token will stay inside the project runtime folder instead of your global Hugging Face cache. Hugging Face documents HF_HOME as the location for token and cache storage. \nHugging Face\n\nUpdated Codex handover prompt\n\nRun this from inside the project folder:\n\nSet up this current folder as a local Python project for a fast DINOv3 + SigLIP2 + UMAP + FiftyOne prototype.\n\nImportant:\n- I am already inside the project root.\n- Do not create a nested project folder.\n- Use the current working directory as the project root.\n- Do not use Conda, Miniconda, Mambaforge, or CUDA.\n- This is for a MacBook M1 Pro.\n- Use PyTorch MPS when available.\n- Keep all machine-specific libraries, model caches, and local app storage inside:\n  _runtime/\n- Do not put the virtual environment in the project root.\n- Create the virtual environment at:\n  _runtime/venv\n- Create Hugging Face cache at:\n  _runtime/hf\n- Create FiftyOne local storage at:\n  _runtime/fiftyone\n- Keep DINOv3 frozen.\n- Keep SigLIP2 frozen.\n- No classifier.\n- No fine-tuning.\n- Goal:\n  images → DINOv3 embeddings → UMAP 2D map → FiftyOne visualization\n  images → SigLIP2 embeddings → optional second UMAP map for semantic/text-aligned comparison\n\nCreate this structure:\n\n_runtime/\n  venv/\n  hf/\n  fiftyone/\n    mongo/\n    datasets/\n    zoo/\n\nimages/\noutputs/\nscripts/\n  check_env.py\n  extract_dino_embeddings.py\n  extract_siglip2_embeddings.py\n  make_umap.py\n  view_fiftyone.py\n\nAGENTS.md\nREADME.md\nrequirements.txt\n.env.example\n.gitignore\n\nSet up the virtual environment:\n\npython3.11 -m venv _runtime/venv\nsource _runtime/venv/bin/activate\npython -m pip install --upgrade pip setuptools wheel\n\nInstall these packages:\n\ntorch\ntorchvision\ntransformers\nhuggingface_hub\npillow\nnumpy\npandas\ntqdm\numap-learn\nscikit-learn\nfiftyone\n\nWrite requirements.txt with those dependencies.\n\nCreate .env.example with:\n\nexport HF_HOME=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/hf\"\nexport HF_HUB_CACHE=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/hf/hub\"\nexport FIFTYONE_DATABASE_DIR=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/fiftyone/mongo\"\nexport FIFTYONE_DEFAULT_DATASET_DIR=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/fiftyone/datasets\"\nexport FIFTYONE_DATASET_ZOO_DIR=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/fiftyone/zoo\"\n\nCreate .gitignore with:\n\n_runtime/\noutputs/\n.DS_Store\n.env\n*.pyc\n__pycache__/\n\nCreate scripts/check_env.py that:\n- prints current project path\n- prints Python version\n- prints torch version\n- prints whether torch.backends.mps.is_available()\n- prints transformers version\n- prints Hugging Face cache path from HF_HOME and HF_HUB_CACHE\n- prints FiftyOne version\n- prints FiftyOne database path if available\n- exits cleanly\n\nCreate scripts/extract_dino_embeddings.py that:\n- recursively scans images/ for jpg, jpeg, png, webp\n- uses facebook/dinov3-vits16-pretrain-lvd1689m\n- uses Hugging Face Transformers AutoImageProcessor and AutoModel\n- uses device = \"mps\" if available, otherwise \"cpu\"\n- uses outputs.pooler_output as the global image embedding\n- L2-normalizes embeddings\n- skips broken images gracefully\n- saves outputs/dino_embeddings.npy as float32\n- saves outputs/manifest.csv with columns:\n  index,path,filename,width,height\n- has CLI flags:\n  --image-dir images\n  --out-dir outputs\n  --batch-size 8\n\nCreate scripts/extract_siglip2_embeddings.py that:\n- recursively scans images/ for jpg, jpeg, png, webp\n- uses google/siglip2-base-patch16-224\n- uses AutoProcessor and AutoModel\n- uses model.get_image_features() for image embeddings\n- uses device = \"mps\" if available, otherwise \"cpu\"\n- L2-normalizes embeddings\n- skips broken images gracefully\n- saves outputs/siglip2_embeddings.npy as float32\n- reuses or creates outputs/manifest.csv\n- has CLI flags:\n  --image-dir images\n  --out-dir outputs\n  --batch-size 8\n\nCreate scripts/make_umap.py that:\n- loads an embeddings .npy file and manifest.csv\n- runs UMAP with cosine metric\n- default parameters:\n  n_neighbors=40\n  min_dist=0.05\n  n_components=2