otype on about 2,000 images.\n- Use DINOv3 global embeddings first.\n- Use SigLIP2 embeddings as a second comparison map.\n- Patch features are a later experiment.\n\nAfter creating the files, run:\n\nsource _runtime/venv/bin/activate\nexport HF_HOME=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/hf\"\nexport HF_HUB_CACHE=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/hf/hub\"\nexport FIFTYONE_DATABASE_DIR=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/fiftyone/mongo\"\nexport FIFTYONE_DEFAULT_DATASET_DIR=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/fiftyone/datasets\"\nexport FIFTYONE_DATASET_ZOO_DIR=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/fiftyone/zoo\"\npython scripts/check_env.py\n\nThen summarize:\n- current project path\n- where the virtual environment was created\n- where Hugging Face models will be cached\n- where FiftyOne data will be stored\n- which packages were installed\n- whether MPS is available\n- whether I still need to run huggingface-cli login\n- the exact next command I should run\n\nAfter you generate the Hugging Face token, first accept access to the DINOv3 model on Hugging Face, then run:\n\nBash\nsource _runtime/venv/bin/activate\n\nexport HF_HOME=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/hf\"\nexport HF_HUB_CACHE=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/hf/hub\"\n\nhuggingface-cli login\n\nPaste the token when prompted.\n\nSources\nSummarize this conversation for a coding agent that needs to build a DINOv3 + FAISS + UMAP image latent-space prototype for Anacronia. Include decisions, unresolved questions, model choices, pipeline architecture, UI ideas, and sources.\n\n\nI’ll turn the discussion into a coding-agent handoff, adding the missing FAISS layer and grounding model/tool choices in official sources.\n\nThought for 2m 55s\nHandover summary for coding agent: Anacronia DINOv3 + FAISS + UMAP prototype\n\nBuild a local MacBook M1 Pro prototype for exploring Anacronia’s visual archive as an unlabeled latent space.\n\nThe goal is not supervised classification. The user has thousands of images saved for fuzzy/aesthetic research categories that are not encoded in folder names. The prototype should generate embeddings, project them to 2D, support nearest-neighbor search, and enable visual exploration.\n\nCore decision\n\nUse this pipeline:\n\nunlabeled images\n→ DINOv3 global embeddings\n→ L2 normalization\n→ FAISS nearest-neighbor index\n→ UMAP 2D projection\n→ visual exploration UI\n\nNo classifier.\nNo fine-tuning.\nNo cloud for the first prototype.\nNo Conda.\nNo CUDA.\nUse Apple Silicon / PyTorch MPS when available.\n\nDINOv3 is appropriate here because it produces high-quality visual features without fine-tuning, and its ViT models return class tokens, register tokens, and patch tokens; for the first prototype, use the global/class-token-style representation, not patch tokens. \nGitHub\n\nUser context and constraints\n\nThe user is working on a project called Anacronia.\n\nThe immediate target is around 2,000 images, local-first, fast prototype.\n\nThe user wants dependencies and model caches to live in a specific project subfolder, not scattered in the project root or global user cache.\n\nUse:\n\nproject-root/\n  _runtime/\n    venv/\n    hf/\n    fiftyone/\n      mongo/\n      datasets/\n      zoo/\n  images/\n  outputs/\n  scripts/\n  README.md\n  AGENTS.md\n  requirements.txt\n  .env.example\n  .gitignore\n\nMeaning:\n\n_runtime/venv        Python virtual environment\n_runtime/hf          Hugging Face token/cache/model downloads\n_runtime/fiftyone    FiftyOne local database/cache\nimages/              input image archive\noutputs/             generated embeddings, indexes, UMAP maps\nscripts/             project scripts\n\nSet Hugging Face cache env vars because HF_HOME controls where Hugging Face stores token/cache data and HF_HUB_CACHE controls where Hub repos/models are cached. \nHugging Face\n\nEnvironment decision\n\nUse standard Python venv and pip.\n\nPreferred Python:\n\nPython 3.11\n\nCreate venv here:\n\nBash\npython3.11 -m venv _runtime/venv\nsource _runtime/venv/bin/activate\npython -m pip install --upgrade pip setuptools wheel\n\nRequired packages:\n\ntorch\ntorchvision\ntransformers\nhuggingface_hub\npillow\nnumpy\npandas\ntqdm\numap-learn\nscikit-learn\nfaiss-cpu\nfiftyone\n\nApple’s PyTorch MPS backend supports GPU acceleration on Apple Silicon, and Apple documents regular pip install torch torchvision torchaudio as the stable install path for current PyTorch on Mac. \nApple Developer\n\nFAISS can be installed via pip install faiss-cpu; the current PyPI package supports Python >=3.10 and is described as a library for similarity search and clustering of dense vectors. \nPyPI\n\nHugging Face access\n\nThe user has created a Hugging Face account.\n\nThey should generate a read or fine-grained read token, not a write token.\n\nReason: DINOv3 model access is gated/licensed, and the local machine needs authenticated access after the user accepts the model terms. Hugging Face documents read tokens for downloading private/gated models and recommends fine-grained tokens for production-style scoped access. \nHugging Face\n\nThe token should not be committed to Git.\n\nUse:\n\nBash\nexport HF_HOME=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/hf\"\nexport HF_HUB_CACHE=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/hf/hub\"\nhuggingface-cli login\nModel choices\nPrimary model: DINOv3\n\nUse:\n\nfacebook/dinov3-vits16-pretrain-lvd1689m\n\nReason: small, likely manageable on MacBook M1 Pro, and enough for a first visual similarity map.\n\nUse DINOv3 as a frozen visual representation model. The official DINOv3 model card describes it as a family of vision foundation models that perform broadly without fine-tuning and produce dense features for vision tasks. \nGitHub\n\nImportant license note: DINOv3 is under Meta’s custom DINOv3 License, not Apache 2.0. The license covers model code, trained weights, inference code, training code, fine-tuning code, and other DINO materials; it allows use/modification/distribution under its terms but includes restrictions around trade controls, prohibited uses, redistribution, reverse engineering, and other obligations. \nGitHub\n\nOptional comparison model: SigLIP2\n\nUse:\n\ngoogle/siglip2-base-patch16-224\n\nReason: generate a second map that is more semantic / language-aligned than DINOv3.\n\nDINOv3 should be treated as the visual-structure map. SigLIP2 should be treated as the semantic/image-text-aligned comparison map. SigLIP2 is a multilingual vision-language encoder family, and Hugging Face documents both image-text outputs and get_image_features() for extracting image embeddings. \nHugging Face\n \nHugging Face\n\nEmbedding strategy\n\nStart with DINO global embeddings only.\n\nDo not begin with patch features. Patch features are a later experiment for local motifs, composition, texture fragments, and recurring visual structures.\n\nConceptual distinction:\n\nDINO global embedding\n= one vector for the whole image\n= useful for overall visual similarity\n\nDINO patch features\n= many vectors for image regions/patches\n= useful for local structures, motifs, repeated shapes, texture regions\n\nThe first prototype should be:\n\nimage → DINOv3 → outputs.pooler_output or equivalent global output → normalized vector\n\nSave:\n\noutputs/manifest.csv\noutputs/dino_embeddings.npy\n\nManifest columns:\n\nindex,path,filename,width,height\n\nEmbedding file:\n\nfloat32 numpy array\nshape = number_of_images x embedding_dim\n\nNormalize embeddings before FAISS and UMAP:\n\nPython\nembeddings = embeddings / np.linalg.norm(embeddings, axis=1, keepdims=True)\nFAISS strategy\n\nFor 2K images, use an exact CPU index first. No vector database needed.\n\nUse cosine similarity by L2-normalizing embeddings and then using inner product:\n\nPython\nindex = faiss.IndexFlatIP(dim)\nindex.add(embeddings.astype(\"float32\"))\n\nFAISS supports vector comparison by L2 distance or dot product, and cosine similarity can be implemented as dot product on normalized vectors. \nPyPI\n\nSave:\n\noutputs/dino.faiss\noutputs/dino_neighbors.csv\n\nNeighbor CSV should contain, for each image:\n\nindex,path,neighbor_rank,neighbor_index,neighbor_path,score\n\nDefault nearest-neighbor query:\n\nk = 20\n\nUse FAISS for:\n\nclick image → show nearest visual neighbors\ndetect clusters\ninspect outliers\ncompare DINO map vs SigLIP2 map\nUMAP strategy\n\nUse UMAP on normalized embeddings.\n\nDefault parameters:\n\nPython\nn_components=2\nn_neighbors=40\nmin_dist=0.05\nmetric=\"cosine\"\nrandom_state=42\n\nGenerate multiple maps without rerunning DINO:\n\nn_neighbors=15    local clusters\nn_neighbors=40    balanced default\nn_neighbors=100   broader/global structure\n\nSave:\n\noutputs/dino_umap.csv\n\nColumns:\n\nindex,path,filename,x,y\n\nFiftyOne’s dimensionality-reduction docs emphasize that embeddings are high-dimensional vectors, 2D projection is for interpretability, and both the embedding model and projection method shape the resulting visualization. \nFiftyOne\n\nUI decision\n\nUse FiftyOne first as a temporary fast viewer.\n\nFiftyOne is not the model and not the embedding method. It is a local interactive visual dataset explorer. It can visualize image embeddings, connect interactive plots to the app, and accept custom embeddings/UMAP workflows. \nFiftyOne\n\nFiftyOne is useful for the first Anacronia prototype because it avoids building a UI before validating that the DINOv3/UMAP visual geometry is meaningful.\n\nAlso note: FiftyOne’s open-source repo is Apache 2.0 licensed, so it is reasonable to learn from or later replace its strategy with a custom interface, respecting license/trademark terms. \nGitHub\n\nFuture custom UI direction\n\nFiftyOne is a prototype viewer, not the final Anacronia interface.\n\nFuture custom visualizer should probably include:\n\n2D WebGL/canvas scatterplot\nimage thumbnails on hover\nzoom/pan\nclick image → nearest neighbors\nlasso selection\nmanual cluster naming\nsaved selections\nmetadata/tag panel\nDINO map / SigLIP2 map switcher\noptional color-palette map\noptional duplicate/near-duplicate detection\n\nThe conceptual UI pattern:\n\nembedding model\n→ 2D projection\n→ interactive image atlas\n→ human interpretation\n→ manual cluster labels\nRequired scripts\n\nCreate:\n\nscripts/check_env.py\nscripts/extract_dino_embeddings.py\nscripts/extract_siglip2_embeddings.py\nscripts/build_faiss.py\nscripts/query_faiss.py\nscripts/make_umap.py\nscripts/view_fiftyone.py\ncheck_env.py\n\nShould print:\n\nproject path\nPython version\ntorch version\nMPS available true/false\ntransformers version\nFAISS import status/version\nFiftyOne version\nHF_HOME\nHF_HUB_CACHE\nFIFTYONE_DATABASE_DIR\nextract_dino_embeddings.py\n\nBehavior:\n\nrecursively scan images/ for jpg, jpeg, png, webp\nskip broken images gracefully\nload facebook/dinov3-vits16-pretrain-lvd1689m\nuse AutoImageProcessor + AutoModel\ndevice = \"mps\" if available else \"cpu\"\nkeep model frozen\nuse torch.inference_mode()\nextract global embedding\nL2-normalize\nsave outputs/dino_embeddings.npy\nsave outputs/manifest.csv\n\nCLI:\n\nBash\npython scripts/extract_dino_embeddings.py \\\n  --image-dir images \\\n  --out-dir outputs \\\n  --batch-size 8\nextract_siglip2_embeddings.py\n\nBehavior:\n\nrecursively scan same images\nload google/siglip2-base-patch16-224\nuse AutoProcessor + AutoModel\nuse model.get_image_features()\nL2-normalize\nsave outputs/siglip2_embeddings.npy\nreuse or create outputs/manifest.csv\n\nCLI:\n\nBash\npython scripts/extract_siglip2_embeddings.py \\\n  --image-dir images \\\n  --out-dir outputs \\\n  --batch-size 8\nbuild_faiss.py\n\nBehavior:\n\nload embeddings npy\nensure float32 contiguous\nbuild IndexFlatIP\nadd normalized vectors\nsave .faiss index\noptionally export top-k neighbors CSV\n\nCLI:\n\nBash\npython scripts/build_faiss.py \\\n  --embeddings outputs/dino_embeddings.npy \\\n  --manifest outputs/manifest.csv \\\n  --index-out outputs/dino.faiss \\\n  --neighbors-out outputs/dino_neighbors.csv \\\n  --k 20\nquery_faiss.py\n\nBehavior:\n\nload FAISS index\nload manifest\nquery by image index or filepath\nreturn nearest neighbors\noptionally copy neighbor thumbnails to outputs/query_results/\n\nCLI:\n\nBash\npython scripts/query_faiss.py \\\n  --index outputs/dino.faiss \\\n  --embeddings outputs/dino_embeddings.npy \\\n  --manifest outputs/manifest.csv \\\n  --query-index 0 \\\n  --k 20\nmake_umap.py\n\nBehavior:\n\nload embeddings\nrun UMAP\nsave map CSV\n\nCLI:\n\nBash\npython scripts/make_umap.py \\\n  --embeddings outputs/dino_embeddings.npy \\\n  --manifest outputs/manifest.csv \\\n  --out outputs/dino_umap.csv \\\n  --n-neighbors 40 \\\n  --min-dist 0.05\nview_fiftyone.py\n\nBehavior:\n\nload map CSV\ncreate/reload FiftyOne dataset\nadd image samples\nstore x/y fields\nlaunch FiftyOne app\nprefer native/interactive embedding visualization if practical\notherwise expose x/y fields and document limitation\n\nCLI:\n\nBash\npython scripts/view_fiftyone.py \\\n  --map outputs/dino_umap.csv \\\n  --dataset-name anacronia_dino\n.env.example\n\nCreate:\n\nBash\nexport HF_HOME=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/hf\"\nexport HF_HUB_CACHE=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/hf/hub\"\nexport FIFTYONE_DATABASE_DIR=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/fiftyone/mongo\"\nexport FIFTYONE_DEFAULT_DATASET_DIR=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/fiftyone/datasets\"\nexport FIFTYONE_DATASET_ZOO_DIR=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/fiftyone/zoo\"\n.gitignore\n\nCreate:\n\n_runtime/\noutputs/\n.env\n.DS_Store\n*.pyc\n__pycache__/\n\nDo not commit Hugging Face tokens, downloaded model weights, generated embeddings, FAISS indexes, or FiftyOne local database files.\n\nREADME command flow\n\nThe README should give the user these exact commands:\n\nBash\nsource _runtime/venv/bin/activate\n\nexport HF_HOME=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/hf\"\nexport HF_HUB_CACHE=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/hf/hub\"\nexport FIFTYONE_DATABASE_DIR=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/fiftyone/mongo\"\nexport FIFTYONE_DEFAULT_DATASET_DIR=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/fiftyone/datasets\"\nexport FIFTYONE_DATASET_ZOO_DIR=\"$(pwd)/_runtime/fiftyone/zoo\"\n\npython scripts/check_env.py\n\nhuggingface-cli login\n\nThen:\n\nBash\npython scripts/extract_dino_embeddings.py \\\n  --image-dir images \\\n  --out-dir outputs \\\n  --batch-size 8\n\npython scripts/build_faiss.py \\\n  --embeddings outputs/dino_embeddings.npy \\\n  --manifest outputs/manifest.csv \\\n  --index-out outputs/dino.faiss \\\n  --neighbors-out outputs/dino_neighbors.csv \\\n  --k 20\n\npython scripts/make_umap.py \\\n  --embeddings outputs/dino_embeddings.npy \\\n  --manifest outputs/manifest.csv \\\n  --out outputs/dino_umap.csv \\\n  --n-neighbors 40 \\\n  --min-dist 0.05\n\npython scripts/view_fiftyone.py \\\n  --map outputs/dino_umap.csv \\\n  --dataset-name anacronia_dino\n\nOptional SigLIP2 comparison:\n\nBash\npython scripts/extract_siglip2_embeddings.py \\\n  --image-dir images \\\n  --out-dir outputs \\\n  --batch-size 8\n\npython scripts/build_faiss.py \\\n  --embeddings outputs/siglip2_embeddings.npy \\\n  --manifest outputs/manifest.csv \\\n  --index-out outputs/siglip2.faiss \\\n  --neighbors-out outputs/siglip2_neighbors.csv \\\n  --k 20\n\npython scripts/make_umap.py \\\n  --embeddings outputs/siglip2_embeddings.npy \\\n  --manifest outputs/manifest.csv \\\n  --out outputs/siglip2_umap.csv \\\n  --n-neighbors 40 \\\n  --min-dist 0.05\n\npython scripts/view_fiftyone.py \\\n  --map outputs/siglip2_umap.csv \\\n  --dataset-name anacronia_siglip2\nUnresolved questions\n\nImage preprocessing\n\nFirst pass: use default Hugging Face preprocessing.\n\nLater compare:\n\ndefault center crop\nsquare padded image\nlarger input resolution\n\nThis matters because Anacronia is aesthetic/compositional, and cropping may alter the latent map.\n\nGlobal vs patch features\n\nFirst pass uses global embeddings only.\n\nPatch features may later support motif-level exploration:\n\nwindows\ngrids\ntextures\nrepeated objects\nspatial layouts\n\nDINO vs SigLIP2 interpretation\n\nDINOv3 map should emphasize visual structure, material, texture, object/scene layout.\n\nSigLIP2 map should be more semantic and text-aligned.\n\nThe user wants to compare both rather than assume one is correct.\n\nFinal UI\n\nFiftyOne is the initial viewer.\n\nA custom Anacronia visualizer may be built later after the embedding/projection strategy is validated.\n\nLicensing\n\nDINOv3 is not Apache; it has a custom Meta license. Do not represent DINOv3 code/weights/derivatives as Apache-licensed. \nGitHub\n\nFiftyOne open-source code is Apache 2.0. \nGitHub\n\nAGENTS.md content\n\nUse this:\n\nMarkdown\n# Anacronia latent-space prototype\n\nRules:\n- No Conda.\n- No CUDA.\n- No classifier.\n- No fine-tuning.\n- Use local MacBook M1 Pro workflow.\n- Use PyTorch MPS when available.\n- Keep all runtime files under _runtime/.\n- Cache all generated outputs under outputs/.\n- Use DINOv3 global embeddings first.\n- Use FAISS for nearest-neighbor search.\n- Use UMAP for 2D projection.\n- Use FiftyOne only as the first temporary visual explorer.\n- Add SigLIP2 as an optional second embedding model for semantic comparison.\n- Keep scripts simple and CLI-driven.\n- Optimize for around 2,000 images first.\n- Patch features are a later experiment.\nSource list\n\nMain sources used for implementation decisions:\n\nDINOv3 model card: model family, no-fine-tuning emphasis, dense features, class/register/patch tokens. \nGitHub\n\nDINOv3 license: custom Meta license and usage restrictions. \nGitHub\n\nSigLIP2 Transformers docs: vision-language model, image/text embeddings, get_image_features(). \nHugging Face\n \nHugging Face\n\nFAISS docs/PyPI: similarity search, clustering, dot product/L2, cosine via normalized vectors, pip package. \nFaiss\n \nPyPI\n\nFiftyOne embeddings and dimensionality-reduction docs: image embedding visualization, UMAP/t-SNE, custom embeddings, interactive app. \nFiftyOne\n \nFiftyOne\n\nHugging Face token/cache docs: read/fine-grained tokens, HF_HOME, HF_HUB_CACHE. \nHugging Face\n \nHugging Face\n\nApple PyTorch MPS docs: Apple Silicon GPU acceleration and install path. \nApple Developer\n\nSources\n\nVoice\nChatGPT is AI and can make mistakes."